To call a C function from your assembly code in a boot loader project, you need to make some modifications to your code and change the way you compile and link it.

First, you need to create a linker script to properly specify the memory layout of your code. This will allow you to set the entry point of your boot loader to 0x7C00. Here is an example of a linker script that you can use:

```ld
OUTPUT_FORMAT("elf32-i386");
ENTRY(start);

SECTIONS {
    . = 0x7C00;

    .text : {
        hw.o(.text);
        *(.text);
    }

    .data : SUBALIGN(2) {
        *(.data);
        *(.rodata*);
    }

    .sig 0x7DFE : {
        SHORT(0xaa55);
    }

    .bss : SUBALIGN(4) {
        __bss_start = .;
        *(COMMON);
        *(.bss);
        . = ALIGN(4);
        __bss_end = .;
    }
    __bss_sizeb = SIZEOF(.bss);

    /DISCARD/ : {
        *(.eh_frame);
        *(.comment);
    }
}
```

Next, you need to modify your assembly code to use the correct entry point and make some changes to the way you call the C function. Here is an example of the modified assembly code (hw.asm):

```assembly
extern print_str
global start
bits 16

section .text
start:
    xor ax, ax
    mov ds, ax
    mov es, ax
    mov ss, ax
    mov sp, 0x7C00

    call print_str ; call function

    cli
    hlt

section .data
name db 'MOS', 0
version db 'v0.1', 0
welcome db 'Developped by Marius Van Nieuwenhuyse', 0x0D, 0x0A, 0
```

Finally, you need to compile and link your code using the following commands:

```
nasm -f elf32 hw.asm -o hw.o
gcc -ffreestanding -c test.c -o test.o
ld -melf_i386 --build-id=none -T linker.ld hw.o test.o -o bootloader.elf
objcopy -O binary bootloader.elf bootloader.bin
```

These commands will compile your assembly code and C code into object files, link them together using the linker script, and then convert the resulting ELF executable into a flat binary file.

You can then run the boot loader using a virtual machine like QEMU:

```
qemu-system-i386 -fda bootloader.bin
```

