I have a SQL table on a database which has a column in it with the Bit datatype. I'm trying to define a method in my C# application that takes two columns from the table as parameters. However, when I try to compile the code, it keeps trying to convert `bit` to `BitConverter`. I also tried changing it to `bit`, but then it has issues accepting it as a datatype. I'm building the application in an ASP.Net Framework solution. Can anyone tell me what I'm doing wrong? Am I referring to the datatype incorrectly?

```csharp
public void Edit_NAA_ApplicationsFirm(int ApplicationId, string UniversityOffer, bit Firm)
{
    //This line declares a variable in which we store the actual values from NAA_Applications based on the associating ID
    NAA_Applications AppFirm = Get_Applicant_Application(ApplicationId);

    //Here we tell the application that the edited values are equal to the values within the table
    AppFirm.Firm = Firm;

    //Any of these changes are then saved.
    _context.SaveChanges();
}
```

**

**

Looks like you're using Entity Framework in your ASP.Net Framework solution.

Entity Framework will use a .NET `boolean` to represent a T-SQL `bit` datatype. This is the correct .NET CLR type to use. When you pass a `boolean` value of `true`, it will be converted to `1` in the `bit` field, and when you pass a `boolean` value of `false`, it will be converted to `0`.

In fact, this mapping between `boolean` and `bit` is documented by Microsoft. You can refer to the following resources for more information:

- [https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/data/adonet/sql/linq/sql-clr-type-mapping](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/data/adonet/sql/linq/sql-clr-type-mapping)
- [https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/cc716729(v=vs.100).aspx](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/cc716729(v=vs.100).aspx)

Therefore, in your code, you should change the parameter `bit Firm` to `bool Firm`:

```csharp
public void Edit_NAA_ApplicationsFirm(int ApplicationId, string UniversityOffer, bool Firm)
{
    // This line declares a variable in which we store the actual values from NAA_Applications based on the associating ID
    NAA_Applications AppFirm = Get_Applicant_Application(ApplicationId);

    // Here we tell the application that the edited values are equal to the values within the table
    AppFirm.Firm = Firm;

    // Any of these changes are then saved.
    _context.SaveChanges();
}
```

By using `bool` as the datatype for `Firm`, you should no longer encounter the conversion issue.

