To find the longest common subsequence between two strings, you can use the following algorithm implemented in Java:

```
// Returns length of LCS for X[0..m-1], Y[0..n-1] 
static int lcs(char[] X, char[] Y, int m, int n) 
{ 
	int L[][] = new int[m + 1][n + 1]; 

	// Following steps build L[m+1][n+1] in bottom 
	// up fashion. Note that L[i][j] contains length 
	// of LCS of X[0..i-1] and Y[0..j-1] 
	for (int i = 0; i <= m; i++) { 
		for (int j = 0; j <= n; j++) { 
			if (i == 0 || j == 0) 
				L[i][j] = 0; 
			else if (X[i - 1] == Y[j - 1]) 
				L[i][j] = L[i - 1][j - 1] + 1; 
			else
				L[i][j] = max(L[i - 1][j], L[i][j - 1]); 
		} 
	} 
	return L[m][n]; 
} 

// Utility function to get max of 2 integers 
static int max(int a, int b) 
{ 
	return (a > b) ? a : b; 
}
```

This algorithm uses a dynamic programming approach to solve the problem. It creates a 2D array `L` with dimensions `(m+1) x (n+1)`, where `m` and `n` are the lengths of the input strings `X` and `Y`, respectively. The value `L[i][j]` represents the length of the longest common subsequence of `X[0..i-1]` and `Y[0..j-1]`.

The algorithm iterates through each character in `X` and `Y` using two nested loops. If the current characters `X[i-1]` and `Y[j-1]` are the same, then the length of the common subsequence is increased by 1 by adding the value of `L[i-1][j-1]` to `L[i][j]`. Otherwise, the length remains the same, and the maximum of `L[i-1][j]` and `L[i][j-1]` is assigned to `L[i][j]`.

Finally, the algorithm returns the value stored in `L[m][n]`, which represents the length of the longest common subsequence between the two strings.

