In conclusion, we have seen how to adapt the Merkle-Damgard hash function in JavaScript and C language to accommodate different hash sizes. The modifications involved calculating the block size and hash size based on the desired hash size, passing the desired hash size as a parameter, and using it in the code. These modifications allow for greater flexibility in the use of the Merkle-Damgard hash function and make it applicable in a wide range of applications.

