```java
public class CheckSorted {
  public static boolean isSorted(int[] arr) {
    if (arr == null || arr.length <= 1) {
      return true;
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < arr.length - 1; i++) {
      if (arr[i] > arr[i + 1]) {
        return false;
      }
    }
    return true;
  }
}
```

The `isSorted` method takes an integer array as input and returns a boolean value indicating whether the array is sorted or not. Here's how it works:

1. The method first checks if the array is null or has only one element. If so, it returns `true`, as an empty or single-element array is considered sorted.

2. If the array has more than one element, a for loop is used to iterate over the array. The loop runs from the first element to the second-to-last element.

3. Within the loop, each element `arr[i]` is compared with the next element `arr[i + 1]`. If `arr[i]` is greater than `arr[i + 1]`, it means the array is not sorted, and the method returns `false`.

4. If the loop completes without encountering any out-of-order elements, it means the array is sorted, and the method returns `true`.

You can use this `isSorted` method in your Java program to check if any given array is sorted or not.

